title: Opening Firefox
content:

I even deleted Firefox and reinstalled the new ESR file. (Am running win 7).

I made a shortcut to the Firefox page using its URL to no avail! What the heck is going on?

I copied the FF URL and made a shortcut to the website and it STILL does not work!

Please help.

THANKS 

                     Ron

title: Google Cloud Monitoring dashboards unusably slow
content:
Hi all! Happy Firefox user for over 20 years here. Recently I've had to switch to Chrome for one of my use cases, Google Cloud Monitoring dashboards. They're evidently JS- and data-heavy, and they're often unusably slow in Firefox. I often see delays of 10s or seconds when clicking any button or link, rendering data, or doing anything else. They also seem to get slower the longer their tab is open in the browser. They're way more usable in Chrome; maybe not perfect, but drastically better.

Any thoughts?

I've used about:performance to take a profile on https://profiler.firefox.com/, and uploaded it to share.firefox.dev , and I know it claims to sanitize personal info, but I'm still a bit leery of posting the link publicly. Happy to share it with a Mozilla employee if that would help.
creator: snarfed

title: Firefox issues in rendering variable font weight (Montserrat)
content:
I encounter a problem with the font rendering of some websites. The problem is similar to [one], however I am on a recent Linux distribution (Fedora 41).

Firefox: 137.0

When browsing, as an example, [OpenMediaVault forum], the Montserrat font is rendered as "thin" (weight 100), even if the style mandates a weight of 400.

The font is rendered properly when Firefox is loading the font from the website (in woff2 format).

If the font is available locally, then Firefox does not scale it and defaults to "thin". Using "Inspect", the weight slider appears but moving it is ineffective.

Now, Fedora ships by default with a non-variable release of Montserrat. However, even replacing it system-wide with the variable version (ttf, in case it matters) taken directly from the Montserrat upstream repo, Firefox still fails to scale it.

Any troubleshooting help would be appreciated.

I don't understand why whatever team that works on Firefox removed keybind settings from Firefox, based on what I have read trying to find a method, keybind settings used to be a thing and then just got removed.

Now I'm sure you have heard everything about this, but have you considered that on your march to the most secure and safe browser, that adding settings for keybinds might be better than having the users crawl the internet for whatever app, shady or not, they can get their hands on to fix it for them. title: Mozilla Firefox
content:
Ich verwende Firefox seit Jahrzehnten und bin sehr zufrieden. Was mich von Anfang an gestört (und ein bissschen geärgert) hat ist, dass es nicht möglich ist, einen url-Link über ein Icon oder eine Tastenkombination zu erzeugen. Früher ging das mit einem Add-on, jetzt nicht mehr.. Der von Mozilla vorgesehene Weg (Fenster verkleinern, auf Desktop ziehen) ist totel antiquiert und umständlich und eine Zumutung. Ich verwende das Add-on QuickCut. Aber das erzeugt html-links. Ich möchte aber Links mit der Endung url haben. Gibt es eine (im Internet vielleicht nicht auffindbare) Möglichkeit oder warum schafft Mozilla diese nicht?

I have been using Firefox for decades and am very satisfied. What has bothered me from the beginning (and annoyed me a bit) is that it is not possible to create a url link via an icon or a keyboard shortcut. This used to be possible with an add-on, but not any more. The way provided by Mozilla (minimize window, drag to desktop) is totally antiquated and cumbersome and an imposition.
